(1369, 2, '2010-05-16 18:09:57', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'I had an enlightening trip to ETH Zurich a couple of weeks ago to visit its excellent <a href="http://www.caad.arch.ethz.ch/">CAAD</a> and D<a href="http://www.dfab.arch.ethz.ch/">igital Fabrication</a> departments. I should start by thanking <a href="http://responsivedesign.de/">Manuel Kretzer</a> for inviting me over and being an great host. After doing a lecture for the CAAD department I was privileged to be shown the exciting and innovative work they''ve been developing over the past couple of years. I had no idea ETH Zurich had such a thriving young Interactive Architecture agenda. Below are a couple of projects from a whole collection of work which you can view <a href="http://www.embedded.arch.ethz.ch/">here</a>.\n\nEagle Sensors - Real-time Sensors Networks on Paragliders by Christoph Wartmann\n\nWireless sensor networks in sick buildings\n\n', 'CAAD Embedded - ETH Zürich', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2010-05-16 18:09:57', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.interactivearchitecture.org/?p=1369', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(962, 3, '2009-08-10 17:02:53', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Last year at the Media Facades Festival in Berlin, I met a guy from Moment Factory, a Media/Arts company based in Monteal. At the time they were working (amoungst other things) with NIN on a number of reactive lighting elements for their tour. I never got to see the result myself (live), but what i''ve seen on youtube makes me wish I had.\n\nTurning their heads towards permanent installation, Moment Factory have recently completed ''La Vitrine'' in Montreal. Now I might like movement tracking and low resolution screens more than most people, but the result here is pretty cool (chevrons, anyone?).\n\nMeanwhile, I wonder how long ''permanent'' is, in this case. 1 year? 10 years? 25 years? If someone from Moment Factory is reading this, please comment!\n\n\n\n', 'MomentFactory', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2009-08-10 17:02:53', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.interactivearchitecture.org/?p=962', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(993, 3, '2009-09-06 23:15:02', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '<img src="/assets/2009/modern02.gif" alt="modern02" title="modern02" width="139" height="85" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-994" />\n\nIn conjunction with The Architecture Foundation, Tate Modern has organised a series of events to discuss the crossroads and collaboration between art and architecture. A series of 6 panel discussions has been organised, three of which have already taken place. The last three will happen in October and November.\n\nIt feels like the collaboration between these two approaches  is something that is changing right now more than ever before. As a part of UnitedVisualArtists, the crossover (grey area?) between art, architecture and design is a topic that comes up all the time, and it''s an area that i''m personally very interested in exploring. It seems that there are a growing number of collectives exploring such cross-disciplinary approaches, and I think it can only be a good thing.\n\nArchitecture + Art: Crossover and Collaboration: Edi Rama and Anri Sala   Monday 19 October 2009\n\nArchitecture + Art: Crossover and Collaboration: The Land: Rirkrit Tiravanija, Hans-Ulrich Obrist and François Roche   Monday 26 October 2009\n\nArchitecture + Art: Crossover and Collaboration: Adam Caruso and Thomas Demand   Monday 2 November 2009\n\n<a href="http://www.tate.org.uk/modern/eventseducation/talksdiscussions/architectureartcrossoverandcollaboration.htm">link</a>', 'Art+Architecture', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2009-09-06 23:15:02', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.interactivearchitecture.org/?p=993', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1291, 2, '2010-03-30 10:20:13', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '\n\nThere are few courses as extraordinarily ambitious as the Interactive Environments Minor a semester-long project at TU Delft organized by the Faculty of Architecture - hyperBODY and Industrial Design and Engineering - ID-StudioLab.\n\n<a href="http://www.interactivearchitecture.org/?attachment_id=1296" rel="attachment wp-att-1296"><img src="/assets/2009/8_6-450x337.jpg" alt="" title="8_6" width="450" height="337" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1296" /></a>\n\n"Throughout the course, three interdisciplinary groups of students supported by TU Delft researchers and guest teachers have designed and built three interactive lounge pavilions. The pavilions attract people to enter, facilitate relaxation and provide a refuge from daily chores."\n\n<a href="http://www.interactivearchitecture.org/?attachment_id=1292" rel="attachment wp-att-1292"><img src="/assets/2009/8_2-450x337.jpg" alt="" title="8_2" width="450" height="337" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1292" /></a>\n\n"Each of these structures is a dynamic system, which communicates with its visitors across different modalities. The installations not only actively adapt to their users’ actions, but autonomously develop a will and behaviour of their own. In this way interactive architectural environments come to life, engaging their occupants in an unprecedented experience of a continuous dialogue with the occupied space."\n\n<a href="http://www.interactivearchitecture.org/?attachment_id=1295" rel="attachment wp-att-1295"><img src="/assets/2009/Odyssey_360lo-450x225.jpg" alt="" title="Odyssey_360lo" width="450" height="225" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1295" /></a>\n\nWhile he''s been too modest to put his name up front on these projects, the real passion and brains behind this project has been Tomasz Jaskiewicz bringing together undergraduate students from a range of degree courses to create a unique design space occupied by programmers, engineers, architects and designers. I look forward to seeing how this evolves in future.\n\n\n\nYou can find out more at <a href="http://www.interactive-environments.nl/">http://www.interactive-environments.nl/</a>', 'Interactive Environments Minor', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2010-03-30 10:20:13', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.interactivearchitecture.org/?p=1291', 0, 'post', '', 0),
