(1384, 2, '2010-06-11 09:56:38', '2010-06-11 08:56:38', '<a href="http://www.interactivearchitecture.org/five-copies-of-digital-architecture-to-be-won.html/1-2" rel="attachment wp-att-1385"><img src="/assets/2009/11.jpg" alt="" title="1" width="450" height="300" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1385" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://www.dezeen.com/2010/06/10/competition-five-copies-of-digital-architecture-to-be-won">Dezeen</a> are running a competition to win copies of my recent book Digital Architecture: Passages Through Hinterlands.\n\n<a href="http://www.dezeen.com/2010/06/10/competition-five-copies-of-digital-architecture-to-be-won">http://www.dezeen.com/2010/06/10/competition-five-copies-of-digital-architecture-to-be-won</a>', 'Five copies of Digital Architecture  to be won', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'five-copies-of-digital-architecture-to-be-won', '', '', '2010-06-11 09:56:38', '2010-06-11 08:56:38', '', 0, 'http://www.interactivearchitecture.org/?p=1384', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1206, 2, '2011-03-18 17:10:01', '2011-03-18 16:10:01', 'Here''s a humorous  list by Tom Igoe of the <a href="http://www.tigoe.net/blog/category/physical%20computing/176/">classic physical computing projects</a> students get excited about every year. I personally recognise a lot of these themes in my own students inital project ideas. Tom being a leading academic in this field of design uses examples of the wonderful work of his students at ITP to demonstrate that even if they might be a little cliched, there is still <a href="http://www.tigoe.net/blog/category/physical%20computing/176/">plenty of imaginative ways to work with these</a>.\n\nI thought maybe I would look at how artists and designers outside of academia have also been been inspired by these themes\n\n<strong>Theremin-like instruments</strong>\n\nThe Hydro-Acoustic Big Bang Filter by the<a href="http://www.interactive-agents.com/">Interactive Agents</a>\n\n<object width="450" height="280"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/oXq5JwE5d9I&hl=en_US&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/oXq5JwE5d9I&hl=en_US&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="450" height="280"></embed></object>\n\n<strong>Gloves</strong>\n\nProbably a little less common now with multi-touch becoming freely available (see below). Also Gloves are great for personal projects but not so good for public ones. Check out <a href="http://createdigitalmusic.com/2005/12/19/controlling-music-with-diy-interactive-gloves/">Peter Kirn''s article</a> on the technology behind these. He rightly identifies the early work of <a href="http://ericsinger.com/biocv.html">Eric Singer</a> and there are links to other pioneers.\n\n<strong>Floor Pads</strong>\n\n<a href="http://www.interactivearchitecture.org/physical-computing%e2%80%99s-greatest-hits-and-misses.html/electroland-2" rel="attachment wp-att-1212"><img src="/assets/2009/electroland.jpg" alt="" title="electroland" width="450" height="230" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1212" /></a>\n<a href="http://electroland.net/">Electroland </a>\n\n<strong>Video Mirrors (This that make people wave their hands)</strong>\n\n<object width="450" height="253"><param name="allowfullscreen" value="true" /><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /><param name="movie" value="http://vimeo.com/moogaloop.swf?clip_id=3576457&amp;server=vimeo.com&amp;show_title=1&amp;show_byline=0&amp;show_portrait=0&amp;color=ffffff&amp;fullscreen=1" /><embed src="http://vimeo.com/moogaloop.swf?clip_id=3576457&amp;server=vimeo.com&amp;show_title=1&amp;show_byline=0&amp;show_portrait=0&amp;color=ffffff&amp;fullscreen=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowfullscreen="true" allowscriptaccess="always" width="450" height="253"></embed></object>\n\n<a href="http://www.msavisuals.com/body_paint">Memo''s ''Body Paint''</a> can be seen at the Decode Exhibition at the V&A Gallery in London.\n\n<strong>Mechanical Pixels</strong>\n\n<a href="http://www.interactivearchitecture.org/physical-computing%e2%80%99s-greatest-hits-and-misses.html/hyposurface" rel="attachment wp-att-1217"><img src="/assets/2009/hyposurface-450x359.jpg" alt="" title="hyposurface" width="450" height="359" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1217" /></a>\n\n<object width="450" height="350"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/JSZg9zgdCSM&color1=0xb1b1b1&color2=0xcfcfcf&hl=en_US&feature=player_embedded&fs=1"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowScriptAccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/JSZg9zgdCSM&color1=0xb1b1b1&color2=0xcfcfcf&hl=en_US&feature=player_embedded&fs=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowfullscreen="true" allowScriptAccess="always" width="450" height="350"></embed></object>\n\nOkay I''ve gone for a classic here choosing the Hyposurface example mainly because I find the commentary on this video funny. There is much better footage online about this project and of course there are many other examples of this kind of work physical pixels such as <a href="http://www.flare-facade.com/">FLARE</a> and <a href="http://www.aether.hu/pgl/">Ping genius loci</a>.\n\n<strong>Scooby-Doo paintings</strong> (Artworks that react to presence)\n\n<object width="450" height="253"><param name="allowfullscreen" value="true" /><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /><param name="movie" value="http://vimeo.com/moogaloop.swf?clip_id=9333075&amp;server=vimeo.com&amp;show_title=1&amp;show_byline=0&amp;show_portrait=0&amp;color=ffffff&amp;fullscreen=1" /><embed src="http://vimeo.com/moogaloop.swf?clip_id=9333075&amp;server=vimeo.com&amp;show_title=1&amp;show_byline=0&amp;show_portrait=0&amp;color=ffffff&amp;fullscreen=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowfullscreen="true" allowscriptaccess="always" width="450" height="253"></embed></object>\n\n‘<a href="http://www.cinimodstudio.com/flutter">Flutter</a>’ by Cinimod Studio plays with the encounter virtual butterflies. The artwork is a product of their on-going fascination with the motion of a butterfly’s flight and the iridescent reflections and scattering of light by the scales on a butterfly’s wing.\n\nBody as Cursor (Tracking and Drawing)\n\nHand as Cursor (Minority Report)\n\nMultitouch Interfaces\n\nTilty Stands and Tables\n\nTilty Controllers\n\nThings You Yell At\n\nHuge dancefloor generating Live visuals controlled by performers voice and other instruments for a range of songs within a set list. In collaboration with U2 lighting designer Willie Williams, <a href="http://www.jasonbruges.com/projects/uk-projects/george-michael-live">Jason Bruges Studio</a> designed the system for George Michael’s live shows.\n\n<a href="http://www.interactivearchitecture.org/physical-computing%e2%80%99s-greatest-hits-and-misses.html/bruges" rel="attachment wp-att-1209"><img src="/assets/2009/bruges.jpg" alt="" title="bruges" width="450" height="363" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1209" /></a>\n\nmeditation helpers\n fields of grass (running your hand across it affects it)\ndolls and pets\nremote hugs\n17. LED fetishism ', 'Physical Computing’s Greatest Hits (and misses)', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'physical-computings-greatest-hits-and-misses', '', '', '2011-03-18 17:10:01', '2011-03-18 16:10:01', '', 0, 'http://www.interactivearchitecture.org/?p=1206', 0, 'post', '', 0),
